prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
We will observe the targets in continuum mode in ALMA band 7, centering the observations at the default 343GHz (873 micron). By performing the observations at a longer wavelength than the peak of the dust SEDs the data will be sensitive to cool dust emission and therefore complement the existing 24micron data (Figure 2). Furthermore, the selected wavelength matches existing and ongoing high-resolution surveys of ~870 and 1100-micron selected sources (e.g. Hodge et al. 2013; Simpson et al. 2013). Therefore, our observations of the 250-micron sources will be analogous with these surveys, and will be used compare the 250-micron selected systems with other populations of submillimeter-selected galaxies (e.g.\ Smolcic al. 2012) Furthermore, the ALMA band 7 primary beam matches the resolution of Herschel at 250 micron, such that we do not have to be concerned with potential counterparts residing outside of the spatial area to which ALMA is sensitive.
The requested resolution of 1'' is sufficient to positionally match ALMA data to the existing imaging in the UDS, which is the main requirement for our science goals.
The requested depth of 0.2mJy/beam is required to solidly detect the galaxies at >5sigma even in cases where the Herschel 250-micron selected source is a blend of 2 to 3 galaxies. The 870 micron fluxes are predicted from fitting various SED templates (Efstathiou et al. 2000; Xu et al. 2003; Poletta et al. 2007). The expectations from SED fitting are consistent with the fluxes that are measured for the handful of sources with coincident ALMA data from ALESS (Figure 1).

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
The Cosmic Infrared Background peaks at ~200 micron, and analyses of the galaxies that comprise this peak are central to understanding the role of dust-obscured sources in galaxy formation and evolution. Herschel-SPIRE 250 micron observations have resolved ~20% of the CIB at this wavelength. Next, to fully understand these sources, a statistically representative sample must be studied across at wavelengths spanning the electromagnetic spectrum. Such a study requires ALMA to reliably identify the individual galaxy counterparts.
We propose band 7 continuum imaging of a statistically complete sample of 100 Herschel-SPIRE 250-micron selected sources in the well-studied UDS field. The unique combination of carefully selected 250-micron targets, ALMA counterpart identification, and the extensive photometric and spectroscopic ancillary data in the UDS is essential to unlock the CIB, by linking the submillimeter information with the archival data.
